title: Lit environments that promote health and well-being
---

A fairly recent paper [1] sought to investigate the photometric and spectral characteristics of the light fields to which people are routinely exposed on a daily basis.

 Working environments were shown to vary substantially in the amount of daylight exposure that they allowed. Those environments with high levels of daylight were found to be supportive of several known measures of non-image forming and visual functioning. Vertical illuminance at the eye ($E_{eye}$) powerfully described the marked difference between natural and open urban environments compared with architectural interiors.
 
The [paper](https://doi.org/10.1177/0143624419896250) is available at https://doi.org/10.1177/0143624419896250 
 

[1] Van Creveld K, Mansfield K. ’Lit environments that promote health and well- being’. *Building Services Engineering Research and Technology*. 2020; 41(2): 193–209.
